  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reflections Written from the Heart
  author: Zhang Tianyi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At eighty years old, my parents return to their native home,
    And my joy at their homecoming grows ever deeper.
    When I present the wine for their long life,
    The nectar seems to overflow like rosy clouds.
    In their silk-robed dance, the banquet hall grows fragrant,
    My idle body finds bliss drunk among the flowers,
    What harm in resting in a simple grass pavilion
    When the world itself is at peace?
    I long to cast my line straight into the clear river,
    And one day, when my hair has turned white,
    I hope to meet King Wen in that distant shore.
  footnotes:
    - The Five Horses (五馬) refers to the traditional rank of provincial governor; the poet's parents have returned home in honored retirement.
    - Ban Yi (班衣) refers to the robes of an official in retirement, worn during celebrations.
    - King Wen (文王) is an allusion to virtuous sage-rulers of antiquity, representing an ideal of peaceful governance the poet wishes to witness.
